description.text:
Inspired by the cooling duct that works by doctek I've remade this from scratch in FreeCad to better suit my needs.

Notable changes:

  • The inner part is now connected at the bottom by 4 small bridges to the outer part. This was mainly done to improve print bed adhesion. An added benefit is increased rigidity for the lower part.

  • Turbine connects at 90 degrees instead of a slope to the air duct. This simplifies the mounting brackets and reduces the overall space taken by the mod.

The mounting system was designed from scratch to match my all steel Prusa. It allows adjustment on all 3 axes and rotating the lower part by about 15 - 20 degrees.

The fan is identical to the one in the original design by doctek, a 50mm x 15mm turbine. Tons of variants on eBay and elsewhere.

This was printed in 1.75mm PET at 245C on 50C bed, 0.3mm layer height. No supports needed.

FreeCad files are included. Enjoy.

Printer:

Resolution:

Notes:

Printed in 1.75mm PET at 245C, bed temp 45C. No supports needed, 100% infill.

Assembly instructions

The hotend is first wrapped in about 10 layers of PTFE tape, then in 2 - 3 layers of Kapton. This provides insulation so the air doesn't cool the hotend itself and also the hotend doesn't melt the air duct.

The air duct was hot glued to the turbine fan. You can do this first so while this cools, you can work on assembling the other parts.

First connect the angle mounting bracket to the coldend top. If you have a different coldend you'll probably have to redesign this bracket a little to match what you have.

Then connect the turbine mount to the angle mounting bracket using 2 M3 screws. I used flat head Phillips screws so they're flush and don't press against the turbine fan. Screw these directly into the angle mounting bracket, no nuts needed. Add 2 - 3 washers between the turbine mount and the angle mounting bracket to provide a bit more spacing for the screw heads. Don't tighten the screws all the way in yet.

Connect the fan to the turbine mount with M3 screws and nuts. I added a couple washers between the fan and the mount to have the air duct perfectly centered on the hotend. Screw these to an almost tight fit, then adjust the Z position so the lower part of the air duct is about 3 mm above the print nozzle. Also you can rotate the turbine mount slightly until the air duct is perfectly parallel to the printing bed. Tighten the nuts all the way.

Adjust the X/Y position by slowly sliding the turbine mount while holding the angle mounting bracket. Tighten the 2 screws that connect the turbine mount to the angle bracket.

description.text:
Wanna learn to draw? Got no talent? Then this is for you. Transform 3D objects to 2D plane is complicated. I do not guarantee you, you will paint like Monet or van Gogh, but the device really works.
It is not my invention, actually, it was used 600 years ago (and may be even before):
http://www.npg.org.uk/learning/digital/portraiture/perspective-seeing-where-you-stand/the-drawing-machine.php
Even such genius like Vincent van Gogh used an alternation of this device
http://www.vangoghreproductions.com/art-techniques/perspective-frame.html

This thing i designed is a modern aproach to this device. Not all parts are printable, you will need:
Plexi (perspex) sheet A4 (ca 21x30cm)
Wooden lath 2x3cm x ca 45cm
4pcs screws M3x25 with nuts
4pcs cable binder 15cm
tripod (in my case Velbon CX 480)
and sure the printed parts

The construction is easy

Draw grid onto the plexi according to your needs (i am using squares cca 5x5cm)
Mount the plexi holder on front end of the lath (screw holes facing forward)
Mount the bracket behind the plexi holder (my bracket is designed for Velbon CX 480 tripod)
Mount the viewer on the lath, the leg piece shuld be mounted on the viewer screw. The needle faces front, away from eye!
Fix the plexi into the holder do not overtighten the screws, i managed to break first prototype of the holder by using too much force here, well, in worst case scenario, you will have to print another holder :D

Moving the viewer back and forth allows to set the viewing angle.

On your canvas, use the same grid, you have on the plexi. Now look through the viewer (adjust the eye by looking over the tip of the needle to the center cross of the grid) the picture is projected on the plexi and the grid helps you to maintain the right perspective. The only thing to do is to copy the projection onto the canvas.

Warning: in our sad world, i have to warn you, do not damage your eye by poking it with the viewer needle, i do not accept any responsibility for any type of damage should you decide to use the device, use common sense, please.

description.text:
Edit 2016-03:
3D-Maze game models designed to be capped with transpatent acrylic sheets at top and bottom. I finally added the source-code with which I generated those mazes.
This was ~5 years overdue!! Sorry for the "slight" delay.
The code is a rather horrible hack - but I checked and it still works.
(The code is public domain) To use it load the haskell source file in ghci (the interactive haskell interpreter) and type "help". To adjust maze size / labyrinthicality / inhomogenity / ... you need to change the source-code since all that stuff is hard-coded. If you want to do elegant idiomatic maze generation in in purely functional programming style (which surprisingly is possible although the problem at first sight seems to require destructive updates) I highly suggest you look at Tikhon Jelvis' work:
http://jelv.is/blog/Generating-Mazes-with-Inductive-Graphs/
https://github.com/TikhonJelvis/inductive-mazes Also there's a second haskell based maze generator model on thingiverse:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:778556 Old text:
The big and probably very hard one (20x10x3 paths) is inhomogenous!
One side (longest axis) has long pathways with few forks and almost no four five and six-way forks (labyrinthical) the other side has lots of short paths dead ends and more four five and maybe six-way forks (mazeical). There is no sharp border between those regions.
The medium sized one (12x12x2 paths) is
overall more "labyrinthical".

Start with the smaller one, the big one took 7h for me.
Make sure bridging works perfectly beforehand!
Don't hatch fill walls.
Reason in instructions of: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15913
Try to avoid fine plastic hair. You wont be able to remove it on the middle layer afterwards. Put a heavy metal ball in, mark the start and finish location to your liking and cap it on both sides with Acrylic or an other transparent material. There are holes for M3 screws to clamp it together. Print it in translucent plastic so that it wont be too hard to use the middle layer.
One could add coordinates on the capping plates like (I/II)-(A..T)(0..9)
And then execute travels like "go from [I-C7] to [II-T0]"
Redesigned screw stop for Z axis. Extended for use with ceramic tile. I'm using it on a Solidoodle 2 with the newer aluminium bed.
I printed it. Then used a few drill bits to get the holes just the right size.

The chin is quite steep, I guess around 45°. This is no problem at usual layer heights, especialy if the overhang is located on a medium convex radius like here.

description.text: customized with 3D Slash!

This is part of the initial design of a bracket to hold a VHF antenna. The bracket will be rail mounted, the diameter of the rail being 19mm. The bracket is in two parts. Other parts are required to complete the unit, these were sourced from an existing mount.
A picture of the existing style of mount is included.
On fitting the unit other improvements have been noted:-
The holes on the lower section could be changed to hex shape to accommodate nuts without them turning. At the time of design the cap screw orientation hadn't been decided.
A further skim could be taken from the mating faces, 0.5mm had already been removed, I would take off another 0.2 to 0.5mm from each face to see if clamping force increases, although it is adequate as it is.
Another modification that could be attempted is the reduction in diameter of the through holes, these are currently 4mm. It was designed with 4mm S.S. cap screws in mind, 25mm long. If one half of the model has the hole diameter reduced, then a screw thread could be applied to enable cap screws to bite into the material without the use of nuts.
If anyone out there ends up designing final part then please share it and let me know.
File format is sketchup 16. ".skp" files won't open in earlier versions - sorry.
Some of the design is pretty crude with small errors, I'm new to the sketchup 3d design and as such some small errors may be present in and around the "teeth" of the model. When printed these are too small to be detected.
I have no idea how this will stand up to the day to day life at sea, no stress analysis has been carried out, therefore if you print this "thing" and use it for anything, you do so at your own risk. (my little disclaimer)

title: Kids Teaching Clock cnc/laser
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The simple construction of a teaching clock relies entirely on press-fitting – no glue needed. The clock hand, with washers in between, is fixed with a self-locking nut.

My build was done on a desktop cnc-machine by Stepcraft from 6 mm birch plywood using a spiral-toothed 1.2 mm flute.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/ for more interesting designs.

The construction itself was done in Solid Edge. For the design of the clock face I resorted to Illustrator using a cool trick:
I inserted the numbers "2 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 9 0 1" with *Type on Path-Tool on a circle and the justification.

Then set the effect to 'Stair Step' and align to middle.

After converting text to path I ungrouped and added the missing 'ones'.

author: ZenziWerken

description.text:
Simple location cube to be imported into Simplify3d (S3d) so that you can find the x,y coordinate of a part.

I use this to find a location to put a seam (the start point of a layer).

Just import the cube into S3d and move it to your desired location. It will show the x,y coordinate.

Enter that coordinate into your FFF profile settings under Layer >>>> Start Points >>> Choose a specific start point.

Preview the part and see how close it is. You may have to shift it a little but it will be generally pretty close!
World of Warcraft

The idea is you print it twice, preferably in different colours, and fit them together. It will look like an impossible dovetail joint. You show the assembled object and ask them how its made and can it be easily assembled and disassembled.
